# MIB-Studio Project Rules

## Code Style Preferences
- Use camelCase for variable and function names
- Use PascalCase for class names
- Use underscore_case for file names
- Indent with 4 spaces
- Place opening braces on the same line for functions and control structures
- Use explicit brace blocks for all control structures, even one-liners

## Qt Integration Patterns
- Keep OpenCV processing code separate from Qt UI code
- Use signals and slots for communication between UI and processing components
- Prefix private member variables with `m_` (e.g., `m_imageView`)
- Prefix UI element member variables with `ui->`

## File Organization
- Place Qt UI classes in src/qt_ui/ directory
- Keep image processing code in src/image_processing/ directory
- Place utility functions in appropriate namespaces

## Documentation Standards
- Use Doxygen-style comments for classes, functions, and members
- Include brief descriptions for all public methods
- Document parameters and return values

## Memory Management
- Prefer smart pointers over raw pointers when ownership semantics are relevant
- Use Qt parent-child relationships for UI component memory management
- Explicitly manage resources in non-UI code

## Threading Approach
- Use Qt's threading model for background operations
- Ensure UI remains responsive during processing tasks
- Use signals and slots for thread communication

## Testing Strategy
- Test OpenCV-Qt image conversion thoroughly
- Verify feature parity between FTXUI and Qt implementations
- Maintain ability to toggle between interfaces during development

## Build System
- Use CMake with proper Qt integration
- Manage dependencies through vcpkg
- Set appropriate Qt-specific CMake flags

## Transition Strategy
- Implement incremental changes with fallback options
- Complete one functional area before moving to the next
- Maintain existing functionality throughout transition 